solution: ```class Solution {
    public int minChanges(int n, int k) {
        if ((n & k) != k) return -1;
        return Integer.bitCount(n ^ k);
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(1)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The key insight is that any bit set in k must already be set in n; otherwise we cannot create that 1 by only flipping 1→0. The bitwise AND check (n & k) == k enforces this. Once valid, the number of differing bits (n ^ k) gives the exact count of 1s in n that must be flipped to 0 to match k.

